        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Experimental boundary conditions documented within ±5% of CFD inputs",
        "description": "Flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, and hematocrit must each be documented in the experimental protocol within ±5% of the values used as CFD boundary conditions."
      },
      "rationale": "The FDA pump PIV and hemolysis bench tests were performed at the identical five flow-speed combinations used in the CFD runs. Experimental boundary conditions are documented in the test reports with measurement uncertainties of ±2% on flow rate and ±0.5 RPM on rotational speed, both within the ±5% acceptance band."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Normalized hemolysis index within validation uncertainty interval at all 5 operating points",
        "description": "The CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) must fall within the combined experimental and simulation uncertainty interval (U_val) at each of the five operating points per ASME V&V 20 validation metric."
      },
      "rationale": "At all five operating points the ASME V&V 20 validation comparison metric E = |D - S| is less than U_val. Maximum E/U_val ratio is 0.87 at the 6 LPM / 3500 RPM point. The validation uncertainty interval accounts for Monte Carlo propagation of inlet velocity profile uncertainty, blood viscosity variability, and experimental repeatability."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI is the primary clinical safety endpoint (absolute NIH) with direct regulatory mapping",
        "description": "The quantity of interest used in validation must be the absolute normalized index of hemolysis (NIH g/100L) that maps directly to the FDA guidance acceptance threshold, not a surrogate or relative metric."
      },
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the absolute NIH (g/100L) as specified in FDA guidance for VAD hemolysis evaluation. The model directly predicts this endpoint; no surrogate mapping is required. The QoI is identical between the validation experiment and the intended COU, satisfying the highest relevance criterion."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/relevance-validation-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activities performed on the same device geometry, fluid, and operating envelope as the COU",
        "description": "Validation must be performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry with porcine blood or a validated blood analog at the five COU operating points. Use of a surrogate geometry or fluid requires documented similarity justification."
      },
      "rationale": "All validation activities were performed on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry (STL file SHA-256 verified) using porcine blood (hematocrit 30±2%) at the five COU operating points. No surrogate geometry or fluid was used. The validation scenario is directly representative of the COU without extrapolation."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/numerical-solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Iterative convergence to residuals < 1e-6 with round-off error bounded below discretization error",
        "description": "All simulations must achieve scaled residuals below 1×10⁻⁶ for continuity, momentum, and turbulence equations. Round-off error estimated via double vs. extended precision comparison must be at least one order of magnitude below the GCI-estimated discretization error."
      },
      "rationale": "All 13 production simulations converged to scaled residuals below 5×10⁻⁷. A double vs. quad-precision comparison on the design-point case shows round-off error of 0.004% on NIH, which is 35× smaller than the 0.14% discretization error floor, confirming round-off is not a material contributor to total numerical error."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Turbulence and hemolysis constitutive model selection justified by literature and sensitivity analysis",
        "description": "The choice of turbulence closure (SST k-ω) and power-law hemolysis model must be justified by published validation studies on blood pump flows, and a model-form sensitivity analysis comparing at least two turbulence closures must show NIH differences within the validation uncertainty interval."
      },
      "rationale": "SST k-ω was selected based on published FDA pump round-robin results (Hariharan et al. 2011) demonstrating superior velocity field accuracy over k-ε variants. A model-form sensitivity comparing SST k-ω to realizable k-ε shows NIH differences of 4.2%, within the 6.1% validation uncertainty interval at the design point. The Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model is the regulatory standard for this device class."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "All influential inputs characterized with probability distributions; Monte Carlo UQ performed with N ≥ 1000",
        "description": "Blood viscosity, inlet velocity profile, rotational speed, and hemolysis model coefficients must each be characterized with a documented probability distribution derived from experimental measurement or literature meta-analysis. Monte Carlo propagation with N ≥ 1000 samples must quantify the contribution of each input to output uncertainty."
      },
      "rationale": "Five influential inputs (blood viscosity, inlet velocity profile shape, rotational speed, hemolysis coefficient C, hemolysis exponent α) were characterized with log-normal or normal distributions fitted to experimental data. Monte Carlo UQ with N = 5000 samples was performed. Variance-based Sobol indices identify hemolysis coefficient C as the dominant uncertainty contributor (S₁ = 0.61), informing future experimental prioritization."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses operator-introduced deviations from the intended simulation protocol (e.g., incorrect boundary-condition entry, mesh import errors). For this assessment, all simulations were executed by a single trained analyst under a documented QMS with independent peer-review of all input decks prior to execution. The SQA factor (assessed at Gradation 4) subsumes the procedural controls that would otherwise be evaluated here. The ASME V&V 40 guidance explicitly permits scoping out Use Error when SQA controls are demonstrated to be sufficient to bound operator-induced variability; that condition is satisfied in this submission."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test Samples evaluates whether the physical test specimens used in validation are representative of the production device population (e.g., manufacturing variability across pump units). The FDA generic centrifugal pump is a reference geometry with no manufacturing variability — it is a single, dimensionally verified artifact used as the community benchmark. Geometric representativeness is therefore not a source of epistemic uncertainty in this validation campaign, and the factor is scoped out as not applicable to a reference-geometry benchmark study. This scoping is consistent with the ASME V&V 40 guidance note permitting exclusion of factors whose governing source of uncertainty is absent by study design."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of Input Parameters assesses whether the boundary and initial conditions applied in the CFD model faithfully reproduce those present in the physical experiment when the two are not identical by design. In this assessment, the CFD boundary conditions were set directly from the experimentally measured values (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, hematocrit) with documented traceability, and the Test Conditions factor (assessed at Gradation 3) formally records the ±5% agreement between experimental measurements and CFD inputs. Because no extrapolation or surrogate mapping of inputs was required, there is no residual equivalency gap to evaluate; the factor is scoped out to avoid double-counting evidence already captured under Test Conditions."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-vad-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-lead-assessor",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All ten assessed credibility factors achieve their required credibility levels (achievedLevel ≥ requiredLevel in every case). The three scoped-out factors — Use Error, Test Samples, and Equivalency of Input Parameters — are each excluded on documented, non-arbitrary grounds: Use Error is subsumed by the Gradation-4 SQA controls; Test Samples is inapplicable to a single reference-geometry benchmark artifact; and Equivalency of Input Parameters is not independently evaluable because experimental and CFD inputs are identical by study design, with residual agreement already captured under the assessed Test Conditions factor. Monte Carlo UQ (N = 5000) quantifies total output uncertainty and demonstrates that the CFD-predicted NIH falls within the combined validation uncertainty interval at all five operating points. The provenance chain from raw PIV and hemolysis bench data through post-processing to the final NIH comparison is fully documented and traceable. On the basis of the complete structured evidence, the credibility assessment team accepts the model as fit for purpose for predicting absolute hemolysis levels in the Class III VAD COU at Model Risk Level 5.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
